Japan's department store sales marked the 26th  consecutive year-on-year fall in April, dropping 2.7 percent to 691.6 billion  yen (6.7 billion dollars), an industry association said Wednesday.
The announcement was based on sales at 272 outlets operated by 118  companies, the Japan Department Stores Association said.
Sales of clothing in April went down 1.3 percent from a year earlier after  falling 4.9 percent in March, while those of furniture plunged 11.7 percent in  April on the previous year, it said.
It remained unclear whether sales at Japanese department stores would  improve in May, the association said.
